MyScript Music

  • SDK
  • Music

    • About MyScript Music SDK

    MyScript Music SDK provides you with the API based on MyScript Music technology, enabling the recognition of handwritten music scores. This section briefly introduces MyScript Music SDK terminology.

    In brief MyScript Music supplies:

    Item Description Â Location
    API for C, Java, and .NET. Music API edk/your_programming_language/
    MyScriptMusic The specific library engine/
    Resource files These files contain specific data needed to perform music score recognition. resources/
    MusicRecognition This code sample demonstrates how to create a document object, create a music recognizer, attach resources and a grammar to it, get the parsed result and convert the score to MusicXML format. edk/your_programming_language/example/music/

    Application blueprint

    The figure below describes how MyScript Music SDK operates.

    You have set the MyScript environment by creating the engine object. A Music recognition with MyScript Music SDK requires that:

    1. you create a Music recognizer. The Music recognizer will analyze the spatial relationships between the parts of the score.

    2. you attach the resources (AK and Grammar) to the recognizer. The data laid down in the resource files inform the recognizer on how to perform the segmentation of all the input ink parts.

    3. you send the strokes and start the recognition that your application has gathered from user handwriting with an electronic pen or a smartphone, tablet or an interactive whiteboard. The recognizer will use a symbol classifier that calculates the probabilities for all the elements in the suggested segmentation and will output a result.

    4. you get back the recognition result in the form of a tree.

    The following describes the main objects of MyScript Music environment in details.

    Environment

    This gives an overview of the main objects of MyScript Music environment. For more details, go to Music document and music elements.

    Music recognizer

    The MusicRecognizer is specialized for music recognition. The recognizer will process the input digital ink as a series of strokes.

    Music Alphabet Knowledge

    Also denoted as âAKâ, this is a special resource file used for recognition of music elements, providing âmusic alphabet knowledgeâ to the recognizer so it is able to recognize the various elements that could possibly make up a music score.

    Music Grammar Knowledge

    The way the score elements can be recognized together is specified by this grammar resource file that is attached to the recognizer.

    Recognition result

    As depicted in the figure above, the result is a score. This is a left to right sequence of composite elements that can be serialized to a MusicXML document.

    The recognition result returned by the Music recognizer is stored in the Music Document. The Document contains a other objects, such as the Score and the Part, that store the recognized music element, stored in the form of tree view.

    Section Music document and music elements gives more details on these elements.

    Check out the code sample provided with MyScript Music SDK to learn how to map the result tree to MusicXML. It is located in the edk/[programming_language_name]/src folder.

    Running a recognition

    A Music recognition with MyScript Music SDK requires various steps hereby described:

    1. Create a Music recognizer, once you have set the MyScript environment through the creation of the engine object. Use the method createMusicRecognizer to create the recognizer.

    2. Load and attach the resources (AK and Grammar) to the recognizer.

    3. Send the strokes that your application has gathered. Use the method addStroke to do so.

    4. Start the recognition using the method process.

    5. Get the recognition result in the form of a tree using the method getScore.

    Check the Tutorial section or the code sample provided with MyScript Music SDK (in the edk/[programming_language_name]/examples folder) to know how to implement the whole Music recognition process.

    Parsing the result

    Steps

    After the recognition process, to explore the resulting tree and go across its nodes, you will need to:

    1- Get the Score
    You obtain the tree after the recognition process thanks to the method getScore (from the Document interface).

    2- Get the Part
    You will use the methods getPartCount, getPartAt if any, from the Score interface, to get the Part contained in the Score.

    3- Go across this Part
    From the Part interface, you can use getElementCount, getElementAt methods (if there is any recognized music element in this Part) to reach the recognized music elements.

    You can convert the tree into a more usable form. We provide a code sample to perform the conversion into MusicXML format. Check in the folder edk/[your_programming_language]/examples/.

    Recognition example

    This section provides you with an example of score recognition.

    Here is an example of a simple score:

    Now, we will imagine that we are going to recognize it using MyScript Music SDK, following the steps described in Overview.

    Now, letâs examine the tree that would be produced. This is a visual example to show you the relationships between the various elements.

    The Document contains the output result, i.e. the score. The Score itself contains the recognized parts (in the current version only one Part can be handled). Then the Part contains all the recognized music elements. This example shows the hierarchical relationships within music elements such as Note, Head, Stem, Beam, Slur and Tie.

    Music document and music elements

    The recognition result returned by the Music recognizer is stored in the Music Document. The Document contains a Score. The Score can be made up of Parts (in the current version, only one part is supported by the SDK). A Part contains different music elements.

    The music elements are stored in the form of tree view. This means that a hierarchical structure in tree form represents the structure of the result, in accordance with the attached grammar resource. The tree describes the nesting structure of the music score.

    Non Music Elements

    The Document, the Score and the Part are engine objects whereas the rest of the nodes are referred to as music elements. You can access these music elements through âgetterâ methods defined in their interfaces.

    Document

    The Document stores the recognition result. The interface of Score provides different methods, among which are the following:

    Method Description
    clear clears this Document instance
    deleteComponentAt delete a component from this instance
    undeleteComponentAt undelete a component from this instance
    getScore returns the interpretation of this instance after it has been processed
    getScratchOut[Count/At] returns the number of active scratch outs or the scratch out. See this section
    add[music element] adds a digital symbol. See this section
    addStroke adds a digital pen stroke to this instance

    Score

    The Score stores the information related to the set of recognized parts. In the current version of Music SDK, only one part is supported. The interface of Score provides two methods:

    Method Description
    getPartCount returns the number of parts in the document
    getPartAt returns the recognized part structure at a specified index

    Part

    The Part stores the information related to the set of recognized symbols. In other words, it contains as many nodes as recognized music symbols. You will find different methods:

    Method Description
    getElementCount returns the number of recognized music elements
    getElementAt returns one music element at a specified index

    Music elements

    Music elements potentially compose a Part. See below the different music elements:

    Accidental Clef Note Time signature
    Annotation Decoration symbol Rest Tuplet
    Arpeggiate Dots Slur TupletBracket
    Bar Head Staff line Â 
    Beam Key signature Stem Â 
    Chord Ledger line Tie Â 

    For a purpose of illustration, we will often display snapshots from our InkTool application.

    Accidental

    An Accidental symbol is defined by its type: flat, sharp, natural, double flat or double sharp. There is one method in Accidental interface:

    Method Description
    getType returns the accidental type value

    Annotation

    The music element Annotation is commonly used for defining the top annotation (beat) and the bottom annotation (beat type) in the Time signature.

    There is one method in Annotation interface:

    Method Description
    getLabel returns the label of the annotation as a string

    Arpeggiate

    The Arpeggiate is defined on Chord objects only. It has a type (normal, up, down, non-arpeggiate) which you can access via the API method:

    Method Description
    getType returns the arpeggiate type

    Bar

    The Bar is defined by its barline location and its bar-style (normal, dotted, end, or start repeat). The bar can be enhanced by an Decoration symbol. Bar interface provides different methods:

    Method Description
    getStyle returns the bar-style value
    getRepeatDirection returns the bar repeat bar direction if any (forward or backward)
    getDecorationCount returns the number of Decoration symbol objects on this bar
    getDecorationAt returns the Decoration symbol object at a specified âindexâ

    Beam

    When a recognized eighth note (or a note of shorter value) is connected to one or multiple consecutive eighth notes (or notes of shorter values), a Beam element appears in the tree view.

    Beam interface provides several methods:

    Method Description
    getPlacement returns the beam placement
    getLeftCount returns the number of lines on the left half of the beam
    getRightCount returns the number of lines on the right half of the beam

    Due to the relational nature of the beam (this is a connection between two or more notes), a single beam instance can appear in the tree view of several notes.

    There is a difference between a Beam element and a beam type. A Beam element is a music element. A beam type is an integer value expressing a notion for graphical representation (begin, end, continue, etc. ). Information on the beam type is stored and reachable from the Note element or the Chord element environments.

    In the example above, ânote 0â and ânote 1â are connected by two beams (thick lines in red between ânote 0â and ânote 1â). On the left, in the resulting score tree view, this is represented as a Beam element that appears in both ânote 0â and ânote 1â trees, as encircled in red. Note that the input range value is the same since it refers to the same Beam element. The beam type value differs depending on the Note: in ânote 0â tree, the type value is begin. This indicates that the Beam element starts from ânote 0â. In ânote 1â tree, the type value is end. This indicates that the Beam element ends on ânote 1â.

    Chord

    The Chord element is composed of different music elements: Head, Stem, Note, Ledger line, Slur, Decoration symbol, Arpeggiate and the Tuplet. Several methods are provided in the Chord interface:

    Method Description
    getDuration returns the chord duration
    getStem returns the chord Stem if any
    getBeamTypeCount returns the number of Beam types on the chord
    getBeamTypeAt returns the Beam at the specified âindexâ
    getStartBeam returns the Beam starting from the chord
    getStoppingBeam returns the Beam stopping on the chord
    getStartSlurCount returns the number of slur starting from this chord
    getStartSlurAt returns the starting Slur at the specified index
    getStopSlurCount returns the number of slurs stopping on this chord
    getStopSlurAt returns the stopping Slur at the specified index
    getLedgerLineCount returns the number of ledger lines for this chord
    getLedgerLineAt returns the Ledger line at the specified index
    getDecorationCount returns the number of Decoration symbol objects for this chord
    getDecorationAt returns the Decoration symbol object at the specified index
    getNoteCount returns the number of notes in this chord
    getNoteAt returns the Note at the specified index
    getArpeggiate returns the chord arpeggiate
    getStartTuplet returns the Tuplet starting from this chord
    getStopTuplet returns the Tuplet stopping on this chord

    In the Chord element environment, Note elements have no Stem, no Head and no Ledger Line elements. Instead, you will find:

    • one single Stem element,

    • different Ledger Line elements and,

    • one single Head element.

    Clef

    A Clef has three different attributes: the symbol that identifies the clef, the line that defines the pitch of the clef and the octave that defines the tessitura of the clef. You find three âgetterâ methods:

    Method Description
    getSymbol returns the clef symbol value
    getLine returns the line on which the clef is positioned
    getOctave returns the clef octave value aforementioned attributes

    Decoration symbol

    A Decoration symbol refers to any of the following symbols:

    • articulation marks: accent, staccato, tenuto, staccatissimo or strong accent up

    • fermatas: normal, angled or square fermata

    • ornaments: mordent, trill mark, inverted mordent, inverted turn or turn

    • technical signs: up bow, stopped or down bow

    The interface provides the following methods:

    Method Description
    getSymbol returns the decoration symbol
    getPlacement returns the placement of this Decoration symbol

    Dots

    The Dots object is associated to a Note element or a Rest element. It increases the duration of this element. One method is provided:

    Method Description
    getCount returns the number of dots

    Head

    The Head is defined by its type value (white or black). One method is provided:

    Method Description
    getType returns the head type value

    Key signature

    A Key signature is identified by its fifth value and its cancel value. The Key signature is also formed of one or several Accidental elements.

    There are three âgetterâ methods for the Key signature element:

    Method Description
    getSignature returns the key signature data
    getAccidentalCount returns the number of accidentals in this key signature
    getAccidentalAt returns the accidental at a specified âindexâ

    The fifths value depends on the set of sharp and flat symbols. When the key signature is defined with sharp symbols, the fifths value is positive. When the key signature is defined with flat symbols, the fifths value is negative.

    The cancel value refers to the number of natural symbols placed on the staff. When natural symbols cancel sharp symbols, a positive value is added to the cancel count. When natural symbols cancel flat symbols, a negative value is added to the cancel count.

    In the following example, the key signature A major has three sharps. The fifths value is thus equal to 3 and the cancel value is equal to 0.

    Below, the key signature G minor has two flats. The fifths value is thus equal to -2 and the cancel value is equal to 0.

    Ledger line

    The Ledger line element is only defined by its input range value.

    Note

    A Note has different attributes and different music elements. Its attributes are the type, the pitch and the duration. A Note can also be formed by different music elements such as Head, Stem, Beam, Ledger line, Slur, Tie, Dots and the Tuplet. These music elements are described below. The following figure depicts some of the possible music elements a note is made of:

    âGetterâ methods are associated with Note interface:

    Method Description
    getType returns the note type
    getPitch returns the note pitch
    getDuration returns the note duration
    getHead returns the note Head
    getStem returns the note Stem
    getDots returns the note Dots
    getAccidental returns the note Accidental if any
    getBeamTypeCount returns the number of beam types on this note
    getBeamTypeAt returns the beam type at a specified âindexâ
    getStartBeam returns the Beam starting from this note
    getStopBeam returns the Beam stopping on this note
    getStartTie returns the Tie starting from this note
    getStopTie returns the Tie stopping on this note
    getStartSlurCount returns the number Slurs starting from this note
    getStartSlurAt returns the starting Slur at the specified âindexâ
    getStopSlurCount returns the number of slurs stopping at this note
    getStopSlurAt returns the stopping Slur at a specified âindexâ
    getLedgerLineCount returns the number of ledger lines for this note
    getLedgerLineAt returns the Ledger line at a specified âindexâ
    getDecorationCount returns the number of Decoration symbol objects on this note
    getDecorationAt returns the Decoration symbol object at a specified âindexâ
    getLine returns the line on which the note is positioned
    getStartTuplet returns the Tuplet starting from this note
    getStopTuplet returns the Tuplet stopping on this note
    getTimeModification returns the time modification for this note. See this section.

    The getLine method defined in the Note interface is different from getLine method defined in the Clef interface (see below figure). Both lines and in-between lines are indexed in the Note interface whereas only lines are indexed in the Â Clef interface.

    The following example shows a Music SDK recognition result including notes recognition. It is displayed through our InkTool application. This example displays the main elements forming a Note.

    The beam type and the Beam element are different. While the beam type is an integer value expressing a notion of graphical representation of the Beam on a given Note, the Beam refers to the Beam instance, i.e. the music element. Given two notes linked by one single Beam, the method getBeamTypeAt returns an integer value, i.e. the beam type. The methods getStartBeam and getStopBeam return the Beam instance (see the following figure). Due to their relational nature, Tie and Slur elements management follow the same principle.

    Rest

    The Rest element is defined by its type and its duration. It can also be enhanced by additional music elements that will be attached to it: the Dots, the Slur, the Decoration symbol and the Tuplet. In the Rest element interface, you find different methods:

    Method Description
    getType returns the rest type
    getDuration returns the note duration
    getDots returns the Dots
    getStartSlurCount returns the number of slurs starting from this rest
    getStartSlurAt returns the starting Slur at the specified âindexâ
    getStopSlurCount returns the number of slurs stopping this rest
    getStopSlurAt returns the stopping Slur at the specified âindexâ
    getDecorationCount returns the number of Decoration symbol objects on this bar
    getDecorationAt returns the Decoration symbol object at a specified âindexâ
    getStartTuplet returns the Tuplet starting from this rest
    getStopTuplet returns the Tuplet stopping on this rest
    getTimeModification returns the time modification for this rest. See this section.

    Slur

    Similarly to the Tie element, a Slur element is defined by its placement (above or below). A Slur is referred to by two Note, or Chord elements.

    The interface gives one method:

    Method Description
    getPlacement returns the tie placement value

    Music elements (Note or Chord) indicate the type of the Slur element they are linked to. This type value is either start or stop.

    In the following figure, ânote 1â and ânote 2â are joined through a slur symbol. On the left, in the resulting score tree view, a Slur element appears in both ânote 1â and ânote 2â trees, as encircled in red. Note that the input range value is the same since it refers to the same Slur element. The placement value is also the same.

    Staff line

    As a reminder, there is no need to handwrite staff lines since the Music SDK provides the addStaff method. As a consequence, there is no âstaffâ element in the hierarchical representation of the Score. Use the addStaff method to specify the staff position in your application.

    Stem

    In the Stem element, the type attribute specifies the stem direction (up or down) and the number of flags. One method is provided:

    Method Description
    getType returns the stem type value

    Tie

    When identical notes are joined together through a tie, a Tie element is created by the Music recognizer. Note and Chord elements indicate the placement of the Tie (above or below).

    The interface gives one method:

    Method Description
    getPlacement returns the tie placement value

    The following figure illustrates a typical case. Here, ânote 3â and ânote 4â are tied. On the left, in the resulting score tree view, a Tie element appears in both ânote 3â and ânote 4â trees, as encircled in red. Note that the input range value is the same since it refers to the same Tie element. The placement value is also the same.

    Time signature

    The recognized Time signature is defined by a beat type and a beat count. The beat type represents the note value of the basic pulse. The beat count represents the number of beats in the bar.

    Method Description
    getType returns the time signature type
    getTop returns the top annotation (beat)
    getBottom returns the bottom annotation (beat type)

    In the following example, the time signature represents five eighth-note beats per bar. Thus, the beat count value is equal to 5 and the beat type is equal to 8. The beat type and the beat count are stored in Annotation elements.

    Tuplet

    A Tuplet has a placement (above or below), a number that it splits the rythmic value into, and a number of brackets (0 or 2). A Tuplet induces a duration change on the objects that it covers. It is referred to by two Note, Chord or Rest elements.

    The interface gives the following methods:

    Method Description
    getPlacement returns the tuplet placement value
    getBracketCount returns the number of brackets on this tuplet
    getBracketAt returns the bracket at the specified index
    getNumber returns the tuplet number

    TupletBracket

    A TupletBracket is defined by its type (start above, stop above, start below or stop below).

    The interface gives one method:

    Method Description
    getType returns the type of the tuplet bracket

    Advanced use

    Recognizing edition gestures

    The scratch-out feature is used to erase several close strokes with a scribble-out gesture, as illustrated on the right.

    ScratchOutDetectionSensitivity controls the scratch-out detection sensitivity. You can adjust the scratch-out feature by modifying the value of ScratchOutDetectionSensitivity. This determines how the engine differentiates between real shapes and scratch-outs. 0.0f disables detection of scratch-outs. 1.0f means maximum supported sensitivity (so it will be more inclined to label strokes as a scratch-out, in case of doubt).

    It is possible to access the ink ranges of both scratch-out strokes and erased strokes.

    Adding digital symbols

    Avoid performing recognition redundantly by importing digital music symbols.

    The interface of Document provides functions for adding digital music symbols:

    Method Description
    addAccidental adds an accidental with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addArticulationMark adds an articulation mark with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addBar adds a bar with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addBeam adds a note beam with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addCharacter adds a digital text character with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addClef adds a clef with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addDots adds dots with respect to their position in this Document instance
    addHead adds a note head with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addLedgerLine adds a ledger line with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addRest adds a rest with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addStaff adds a staff in this Document instance by defining line position
    addStem adds a note stem with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addTieOrSlur adds a note tie or a slur with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addTimeSignature adds a time signature with respect to its position in this Document instance
    addTupletBracket adds a tuplet bracket with respect to its position in this Document instance

    These methods are useful when part of the input digital ink has already been processed and recognized. At some point new input ink is appended. With these methods, you reduce the recognition processing time, since only the appended ink is processed by the recognizer through the addStroke function.

    See the figure below.

    Getting tuplet time modification

    Tuplet objects change the duration of the objects they span, namely Note and/or Rest objects. The interfaces of these objects provide the method getTimeModifcationthat returns the time modification for this note or rest. This method requires data such as:

    • the actual, that corresponds to the number that divides the beat,

    • the normal, that is the numerical ratio, if indicated. It shows how many time values of the tuplet are normally included in the part of the beat in question.

    • the dots, that indicates the number of dots on the note or rest,

    • the type, that refers to the intrinsic time value of this note or rest.

    This is illustrated below:

    When the symbol corresponding to the normal value is not explicitly written, the recognizer tries to estimate it. However, if it does not find an estimate, it assigns the value of actual minus 1, as illustrated below:

    In case the writer provides a tuplet that is not correct in the sense of music notation, the value of type is UNKNOWN.

    Getting the input range

    All music elements have an input range value. The input range value represents the sets of strokes defining the corresponding music element.

    The examples hereunder show a handwritten treble clef and a quarter note. The treble clef is composed of one stroke, made of sixteen points (ranged from 0 to 15). The input range for the treble clef would be (0:0 - 0:15) or more explicitly Stroke 0, Point 0 up to Stroke 0, Point 15.

    In the case of the note, the head stroke is drawn first (stroke 0), then the stem (stroke 1). The input range of this note would be (0:0 - 0:11, 1:0 - 1:5), which means Stroke 0, Point 0 up to Stroke 0, Point 11 and Stroke 1, Point 0 up to Stroke 1, Point 5.

    You can clearly see the stroke and point order of an ink sample using InkTool. You can also see the input range in the recognition result hierarchy after recognizing an ink sample in the result data structure.

    The following methods are available for any music element:

    Method Description
    getInputRangeCount returns the number of input ranges this element covers
    getInputRangeAt returns the input range at the specified index
